      "content": "yeah i agree it's a nuance thing. but i was talking to some people earlier and they were saying that even if you study it academically, in the \"real world\"—like in high-level jobs or professional settings—the people who speak like text b are just seen as less capable or less educated compared to people who speak like text a. \n\nis that just a social bias we need to fix, or is there actually a reason why text a represents a higher level of cognitive or intellectual skill? like, is there an inherent link between using complex grammar and being more \"intelligent\"?",
